    <!-- Northern Stories Section -->
    <section id="northern-stories" class="py-20 bg-amber-50">
        <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
            <h3 class="text-5xl font-bold text-center text-red-900 mb-16 section-title">Tales from Northern India</h3>
            <div class="story-section">
                <!-- Story 1: Bopoluchi (Punjab) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">Bopoluchi: The Bride’s Revenge (Punjab)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In the heart of Punjab’s golden mustard fields, where village wells buzz with chatter and Bhangra rhythms echo during Lohri, the tale of Bopoluchi is a cherished gem. Shared by women weaving phulkari shawls, it celebrates the wit of a young girl in a vibrant community. Bopoluchi, a lively lass, was fetching water one evening when her friends teased her about her dreams of a grand wedding. A cunning thief, lurking behind a banyan tree, overheard and saw his chance. Dressed in silks and fake jewels, he posed as a wealthy merchant and charmed Bopoluchi’s family with tales of distant riches. The village, swept up in the excitement, celebrated their wedding with dhol drums and laddoos. But soon, Bopoluchi noticed her husband slipping out at night. Curious, she trailed him to a cave filled with stolen treasures. Determined to protect her family, she hatched a plan. She invited the village elders to a feast, claiming to unveil her husband’s wealth. Luring the thief into a heavy chest with promises of hidden gems, she locked him inside and summoned the villagers. The thief, trapped, confessed his crimes, and Bopoluchi’s quick thinking saved her honor. The village hailed her as a heroine, and her story spread, sung in folk ballads. <strong>Moral:</strong> Cleverness triumphs over deceit. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> This tale reflects Punjab’s communal wells, sarson ka saag feasts, and storytelling under starry skies, where laughter and dhol beats unite the village.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 2: The Clever Jackal (Rajasthan) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Clever Jackal (Rajasthan)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Rajasthan’s sun-baked villages, where mud huts glow under starry skies and Bhopas weave tales with ravanhattho fiddles, the story of the Clever Jackal is a desert favorite, told during Pushkar Mela’s camel fairs. It mirrors the cunning needed to survive the Thar’s harsh sands. A scrawny jackal, always hungry, wandered into a village dyer’s yard and tumbled into a vat of indigo dye. Emerging with a dazzling blue coat, he strutted into the forest, proclaiming himself a divine guardian sent by the gods. Lions, elephants, and peacocks, awed by his shimmering fur, crowned him their king, offering fruits and shade. The jackal basked in glory, lounging under neem trees. But one monsoon night, a fierce storm washed away the dye, exposing his ordinary self. The animals, enraged at the trick, chased him across the dunes. The jackal, ever sly, slipped into a narrow cave, laughing as the larger beasts couldn’t follow. He escaped, vowing to keep his tricks subtler, though his mischievous glint never faded. <strong>Moral:</strong> Truth outlasts deception. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale evokes Rajasthan’s bandhani fabrics, desert campfires, and Ghoomar dances, with storytelling as a communal ritual in mud-walled courtyards.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 3: The Sage’s Daughter (Uttar Pradesh) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Sage’s Daughter (Uttar Pradesh)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        Along the sacred Ganges in Uttar Pradesh, where villagers gather for Kumbh Mela and recite Katha tales by flickering diyas, the Sage’s Daughter is a beloved story, inspired by Panchatantra wisdom. It reflects the region’s spiritual depth and sugarcane fields. A revered sage, meditating under a peepal tree, saw a hawk drop a tiny mouse into the river. With his mystic powers, he transformed the mouse into a radiant girl and raised her with love, teaching her the Vedas. When she came of age, the sage sought a husband worthy of her. He approached the Sun God, whose light warmed the fields, but the Sun bowed to the Cloud God, who could dim his rays. The Cloud praised the Wind God, who scattered clouds. The Wind revered the Mountain God, unmoved by his gusts. But the Mountain admitted the Mouse King was mightiest, for his burrows could topple peaks. The sage, seeing the girl’s true essence, returned her to mouse form. She happily wed the Mouse King, scampering off to a simple life in the fields. <strong>Moral:</strong> True worth lies in embracing one’s origins. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale captures Uttar Pradesh’s river ghats, tulsi shrines, and devotional bhajans, with storytelling under moonlit mango groves.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 4: The Ghost of Kinnaur (Himachal Pradesh) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Ghost of Kinnaur (Himachal Pradesh)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In the snowy villages of Himachal’s Kinnaur, where Buddhist prayer flags flutter and Losar festivals warm winter nights, the Ghost of Kinnaur is told around crackling bonfires, blending Hindu and Buddhist lore. A greedy merchant, hoarding gold in his stone mansion, ignored his village’s pleas for aid during a harsh winter. After his death, his spirit haunted the apple orchards, demanding offerings and unleashing blizzards that withered crops. The villagers, trembling, left food at his doorstep, but the ghost’s greed grew. A young shepherd, trained by a lama, decided to act. The lama gave him a sacred mantra and a sack of stone “gold” coins. At midnight, the shepherd faced the ghost, offering the fake gold in exchange for peace. As the ghost reached for the sack, the shepherd chanted the mantra, weakening the spirit. The ghost, seeing its folly, dissolved into the mountain mist, and the orchards bloomed. The shepherd shared his wool, and the village thrived. <strong>Moral:</strong> Generosity frees the soul; greed binds it. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale reflects Himachal’s monasteries, yak caravans, and Nati dances, with storytelling in cozy, shawl-wrapped gatherings.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 5: The Magic Mango (Haryana) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Magic Mango (Haryana)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Haryana’s fertile villages, where Baisakhi brings joyous harvests and Giddha dances, the Magic Mango is a beloved tale told under peepal trees during hookah sessions. It celebrates the region’s agricultural spirit. A kind farmer named Ramu, toiling in his orchard, found a glowing mango that granted wishes when eaten. He shared its fruits with his starving village, filling granaries and hearts. A greedy landlord, envious, tricked Ramu into a feast at his haveli, planning to steal the mango. Ramu, sensing danger, offered the landlord a wish, but warned that selfish desires would backfire. The landlord wished for endless gold, but the mango, angered by his greed, turned his riches to dust. The villagers, rallied by Ramu, chased the landlord away, and the mango tree bore more fruit, shared equally. The landlord, humbled, worked the fields, learning kindness. <strong>Moral:</strong> Sharing brings true wealth. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale evokes Haryana’s wheat fields, jaggery sweets, and communal storytelling, with women in colorful ghagrobotics: Giddha dancers performing in a Haryana village.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 6: The Singing Sparrow (Uttarakhand) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Singing Sparrow (Uttarakhand)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Uttarakhand’s Kumaoni hills, where Phool Dei festivals celebrate nature and Pandva Nritya echoes, the Singing Sparrow is shared in terraced villages, reflecting harmony with the Himalayas. A sparrow named Chhoti, with a voice like a flute, sang in a cedar tree, healing the sick with her melodies. A cruel hunter, seeking profit, caged her, but her songs weakened in captivity. The village children, hearing her faint notes, plotted her escape. One night, they distracted the hunter with a mock fire and freed Chhoti. Her joyous song returned, summoning rains to end a drought. The hunter, shamed, planted trees to atone, and Chhoti’s melodies blessed the harvests. The children made her a nest, and her songs rang through the hills. <strong>Moral:</strong> Freedom nurtures life; captivity dims it. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale captures Uttarakhand’s oak forests, chardham pilgrimages, and storytelling with devotional jagar music, amidst rhododendron blooms.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Southern Stories Section -->
    <section id="southern-stories" class="py-20 bg-rose-50">
        <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
            <h3 class="text-5xl font-bold text-center text-red-900 mb-16 section-title">Tales from Southern India</h3>
            <div class="story-section">
                <!-- Story 1: The Monkey and the Coconut Grove (Tamil Nadu) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Monkey and the Coconut Grove (Tamil Nadu)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Tamil Nadu’s lush villages, where Pongal brings kolam-decorated courtyards and Bharatanatyam graces temples, the Monkey and the Coconut Grove is a Panchatantra tale told by the Kaveri River. A clever monkey named Mani lived in a coconut grove, sipping sweet water from the treetops. A greedy crocodile, basking in the river, envied Mani’s carefree life and offered to ferry him to an island with juicier coconuts. Mani, wary but curious, hopped onto the crocodile’s back. Midstream, the crocodile grinned, planning to drown Mani and claim the grove. Mani, quick-witted, exclaimed, “Alas, I left my heart in the tree! Turn back!” The gullible crocodile swam back, and Mani leapt to safety, pelting the crocodile with coconuts. The village children, watching, sang Mani’s praises, and the crocodile slunk away, tail between legs. Mani shared his coconuts, and the grove became a village haven. <strong>Moral:</strong> Wit outsmarts greed. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale reflects Tamil Nadu’s palm-fringed rivers, banana leaf feasts, and Carnatic music, with storytelling in vibrant silk saree-clad gatherings.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 2: The Magic Drum (Karnataka) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Magic Drum (Karnataka)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Karnataka’s coffee-scented villages, where Ugadi sparks Yakshagana performances, the Magic Drum is told under banyan trees during starry fairs. Gopi, a poor drummer, found a enchanted drum in a forest near his village’s coffee plantations. Each beat conjured food, clothes, and jewels, transforming his hungry village into a place of plenty. A selfish landlord, hearing of the drum, invited Gopi to his grand haveli, plotting to steal it. Gopi, sensing the trap, played a mischievous tune, turning the landlord’s gold to sand. The landlord’s guards chased Gopi, but a second tune summoned monkeys to scatter them. Gopi shared the drum’s gifts, building wells and schools. The landlord, humbled, joined the village, learning to drum for joy, not greed. The drum’s magic faded, but Gopi’s rhythms kept the village alive. <strong>Moral:</strong> Generosity builds lasting prosperity. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale evokes Karnataka’s Western Ghats, jasmine garlands, and Veena melodies, with storytelling amidst filter coffee and dosa aromas.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 3: The Clever Parrot (Andhra Pradesh) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Clever Parrot (Andhra Pradesh)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Andhra Pradesh’s coastal villages, where Sankranti kites soar and Kuchipudi dancers perform, the Clever Parrot is shared under palm trees during fish market bustle. Chitra, a parrot with a gift for mimicry, lived in a mango tree, delighting her village with songs. A wicked merchant, seeking riches, caged her to sell her talents. Chitra, observant, overheard the merchant plotting to sell fake pearls to the village chief. At the chief’s court, she mimicked the merchant’s voice, confessing his scheme. The chief, laughing, freed Chitra and banished the merchant, who lost his fortune. Chitra returned, her songs warning of danger and cheering harvests. The villagers guarded her grove, and the merchant, reformed, became a humble fisherman, learning honesty. Chitra’s melodies became a village treasure. <strong>Moral:</strong> Truth and cleverness protect the just. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale captures Andhra’s paddy fields, gongura pickles, and storytelling with turmeric-stained hands and coastal breezes.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 4: The Turtle’s Wisdom (Kerala) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Turtle’s Wisdom (Kerala)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Kerala’s backwater villages, where Onam feasts and Kathakali dramas unfold, the Turtle’s Wisdom is told on houseboat decks, reflecting the region’s lush harmony. Kuttan, a wise turtle, lived in a lotus pond near a village of coconut palms. When a drought parched the land, animals panicked, but Kuttan listened calmly. He overheard birds chattering about a hidden forest spring. Kuttan rallied the animals to dig a channel to the spring. A proud elephant boasted he could carry the water alone, ignoring Kuttan’s call for teamwork. The elephant collapsed, exhausted, and the animals, inspired by Kuttan’s patience, dug together, guiding the spring’s water to the village. The pond refilled, and crops flourished. The elephant, chastened, thanked Kuttan, and the village held a snake boat race in his honor. <strong>Moral:</strong> Cooperation and wisdom save the day. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale evokes Kerala’s emerald backwaters, Mohiniyattam music, and banana chip feasts, with storytelling on palm-fringed shores.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 5: The Golden Sparrow (Telangana) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Golden Sparrow (Telangana)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Telangana’s vibrant villages, where Bathukamma festivals bloom with marigold stacks, the Golden Sparrow is told under tamarind trees, reflecting the region’s cotton fields and folk dances. A poor weaver named Lakshmi found a sparrow with golden feathers in her loom shed. Its song brought rain, reviving her drought-hit village. A greedy moneylender, eyeing the sparrow, offered Lakshmi a loan to trap it. Lakshmi, wise and kind, refused, sharing the sparrow’s blessings. The moneylender, furious, tried to cage the sparrow, but its song summoned a storm, flooding his mansion. The village, united by Lakshmi’s honesty, rebuilt together, and the sparrow’s feathers adorned their festival idols. The moneylender, reformed, wove with Lakshmi, learning humility. The sparrow’s song echoed through bountiful harvests. <strong>Moral:</strong> Honesty nurtures prosperity. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale captures Telangana’s red-soil fields, Pochampally sarees, and storytelling with Dandiya dances and spicy mirchi bajjis.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 6: The Fisherman’s Lamp (Puducherry) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Fisherman’s Lamp (Puducherry)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Puducherry’s coastal hamlets, where French-inspired villas meet Tamil traditions, the Fisherman’s Lamp is shared during Deepavali, with oil lamps lighting sandy shores. A fisherman named Ravi found a glowing lamp in his net while fishing under a full moon. Its light guided him to abundant catches, feeding his village. A cunning trader, craving the lamp, offered Ravi gold to buy it. Ravi, sensing greed, refused, using the lamp to guide all fishermen. The trader, enraged, stole the lamp, but its light dimmed in his hands. Ravi, with the village’s help, confronted the trader, who confessed, shamed. The lamp’s glow returned, illuminating the coast. The trader, reformed, joined the fishermen, and the lamp’s light blessed their nets. <strong>Moral:</strong> Selflessness shines brightest. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale reflects Puducherry’s beaches, Auroville serenity, and storytelling with Tamil folk songs and Franco-Tamil creole feasts.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>
    <!-- Eastern Stories Section -->
    <section id="eastern-stories" class="py-20 bg-teal-50">
        <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
            <h3 class="text-5xl font-bold text-center text-red-900 mb-16 section-title">Tales from Eastern India</h3>
            <div class="story-section">
                <!-- Story 1: The Clever Fox (West Bengal) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Clever Fox (West Bengal)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In West Bengal’s lush villages, where Durga Puja brings pandals and Dhak drums, the Clever Fox is told by the Hooghly River. A fox named Kumud, living in the Sundarbans, was known for her cunning. A greedy fisherman planned to trap her for her pelt. Kumud, overhearing, left fish scraps by his boat, making him think his nets were cursed. Panicked, he fled, and Kumud led the village to the fish, feeding all. The fisherman, shamed, shared his catches, and Kumud’s cleverness was sung in Baul songs. <strong>Moral:</strong> Wit aids the community. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale evokes West Bengal’s mangroves, jute fields, and Rabindra Sangeet with mishti feasts.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 2: The Magic Flute (Odisha) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Magic Flute (Odisha)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Odisha’s coastal villages, where Rath Yatra enlivens Puri, the Magic Flute is told during Odissi dance recitals. Gopal, a poor flutist, found a flute that charmed animals to work fields, enriching his village. A jealous priest stole it, but the flute played sour notes for him. Gopal’s honest tune called the animals back, exposing the priest. The village forgave him, and Gopal’s music blessed harvests. <strong>Moral:</strong> Honesty resonates true. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale captures Odisha’s Chilika Lake, Pattachitra art, and storytelling with mahaprasad.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 3: The Talking Tree (Assam) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Talking Tree (Assam)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Assam’s tea gardens, where Bihu dances celebrate harvests, the Talking Tree is told by Brahmaputra’s banks. A banyan tree whispered wisdom to Lila, a kind girl. A greedy trader planned to cut it for timber. Lila, guided by the tree, planted false rumors of a curse. The trader fled, and Lila shared the tree’s advice, improving crops. The trader, humbled, planted trees. <strong>Moral:</strong> Wisdom protects nature. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale reflects Assam’s tea estates, xatriya dances, and storytelling with pithas.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 4: The Brave Deer (Jharkhand) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Brave Deer (Jharkhand)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Jharkhand’s tribal villages, where Sohrai festivals paint mud walls, the Brave Deer is told by bonfires. A deer named Hiran saved her village by luring a tiger away from children. A hunter, seeking her antlers, trapped her. The children, grateful, freed her, scaring the hunter with drumbeats. Hiran’s courage inspired the hunter to protect forests. <strong>Moral:</strong> Courage saves lives. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale evokes Jharkhand’s forests, Santhal dances, and storytelling with rice beer.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 5: The Wise Crow (Bihar) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Wise Crow (Bihar)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Bihar’s villages, where Chhath Puja honors the sun, the Wise Crow is told by Ganges banks. A crow named Kala found a pot too narrow for her beak. She dropped pebbles to raise the water, teaching villagers to solve a drought by digging wells. A greedy landlord claimed her idea, but Kala exposed him by repeating his boasts. He reformed, and wells flourished. <strong>Moral:</strong> Ingenuity benefits all. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale captures Bihar’s fields, Madhubani art, and storytelling with litti-chokha.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 6: The Singing Frog (Tripura) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Singing Frog (Tripura)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Tripura’s lush villages, where Durga Puja sparks Hojagiri dances, the Singing Frog is told by rice paddies. A frog named Tuni sang to warn of floods. A trader caged her for profit, but her silence brought drought. Villagers freed her, and her song summoned rain. The trader, shamed, built canals, and Tuni’s song blessed fields. <strong>Moral:</strong> Freedom brings harmony. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale reflects Tripura’s bamboo huts, handlooms, and storytelling with fish curries.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Western Stories Section -->
    <section id="western-stories" class="py-20 bg-indigo-50">
        <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
            <h3 class="text-5xl font-bold text-center text-red-900 mb-16 section-title">Tales from Western India</h3>
            <div class="story-section">
                <!-- Story 1: The Clever Weaver (Gujarat) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Clever Weaver (Gujarat)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Gujarat’s vibrant villages, where Navratri sparks Garba dances, the Clever Weaver is told by looms. Weaver Nila crafted a cloth that glowed at night, drawing crowds. A merchant offered gold to steal her secret, but Nila wove a trap, making a cloth that tangled him. She freed him, and he shared profits, boosting the village. <strong>Moral:</strong> Skill protects integrity. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale evokes Gujarat’s Patola sarees, dandiya nights, and storytelling with dhokla.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 2: The Talking Peacock (Maharashtra) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Talking Peacock (Maharashtra)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Maharashtra’s villages, where Ganesh Chaturthi brings modaks, the Talking Peacock is told by Sahyadri hills. A peacock named Mor warned of a landslide. A hunter caged him for fame, but Mor’s silence brought drought. Villagers freed him, and his dance brought rain. The hunter built shelters, and Mor’s cries guarded the village. <strong>Moral:</strong> Freedom aids all. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale captures Maharashtra’s Warli art, lavani dances, and storytelling with puran poli.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <!-- Story 3: The Magic Coconut (Goa) -->
                <div class="story-card rounded-xl shadow-xl p-8">
                    <h4 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-purple-800 mb-4">The Magic Coconut (Goa)</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        In Goa’s coastal villages, where Carnival brings feni, the Magic Coconut is told by beaches. Fisher Maria found a coconut that multiplied fish. A trader stole it, but it yielded rotten fish. Maria’s honesty returned it, and she fed the village. The trader, reformed, fished, and the coconut blessed nets. <strong>Moral:</strong> Honesty yields abundance. <strong>Cultural Elements:</strong> The tale reflects Goa’s beaches, Konkani songs, and storytelling with fish curry.
                    </p>
                </div>

